article.description: Villanova shot rocks in the first half, but rolled in the second to knock off George Washington.
article.headline: Everyone chips in for 'Nova's first Sweet 16 trip
article.linkText: Villanova warms up from long range, drops Colonials
article.story:
NORMAN, Okla. (AP) -- An old friend -- the 3-point shot -- helped
carry Villanova's women to the NCAA round of 16 for the first time.

	   After going 3-of-12 from 3-point range in the first half, the
Wildcats made eight long-range shots in the final 20 minutes to
beat George Washington 70-57 at the Mideast Regional.

	   Katie Davis scored 24 points, Trish Juhline had 14 of her 16 in
the second half, and Jennifer Hilgenberg scored a career-high 14
for second-seeded Villanova (27-5).

	   The Wildcats advance to play Colorado in the regional semifinals
Saturday in Knoxville, Tenn.

	   Villanova, which averages nearly nine 3-pointers per game, got
an unexpected lift from Hilgenberg, who was 0-for-4 from that range
during the season.

	   She made both her 3-point tries against the seventh-seeded
Colonials (25-7). One came at the end of a stretch of six
3-pointers that gave Villanova control in the second half. The
other started a clinching run after George Washington had cut the
deficit to nine with under eight minutes left.

	   "I told our team, to win we need other players to step up,''
coach Harry Perretta said. "All the kids that come off the bench,
we need them offensively.

	   "Today Jennifer gave us the offense we needed to get us over
the top.''

	   Villanova had a tough time getting good shots from the perimeter
in the first half. Then the Wildcats missed their first four shots
of the second half before getting six 3s in a span of 4½ minutes to
take control.

	   Davis had three of the long-range shots and Juhline, just
1-for-8 from the field in the first half, added two as the Wildcats
took a 47-35 lead with just under 12 minutes remaining.

	   "I thought we came out real strong in the second half,''
Colonials coach Joe McKeown said. "They answered with a barrage of
3s and it just kind of got away from us. You've got to give them a
lot of credit.''

	   Ugo Oha, who finished with 21 points, scored 10 straight points
for the Colonials to keep them within range at 53-44. Then
Hilgenberg made her second 3-pointer to start a 9-2 run that pushed
the lead to 16 with 4:14 to play.

	   George Washington didn't get within single digits after that.

	   Oha had just four points at halftime because she got her second
foul and sat down with 12:25 left.

	   The Colonials had a 13-10 lead shortly after Oha went out, but
Villanova opened a 27-20 advantage before going to halftime with a
27-23 lead.

	   Courtney Mix had 11 points and nine rebounds for Villanova. Anna
Montanana scored 15 for the Colonials.
